From the high school admission process to having what it takes to succeed in high school.

2.	<strong>How is the course organized?</strong> – The course is organized into 4 levels: 1) Who Am I? 2) What Do I Want? 3) How Can I Get There? 4) What Do I Need to Do? Higher levels ask you to use things you learned in lower levels. It may be helpful to think of a level as a module, or unit of work. To complete a level you must complete and submit a few quests, which are the learning activities that will help you achieve the goals of the level. 

3.	<strong>How do I start working?</strong> – Click “The Course” on the top navigation bar. This will take you to a welcome page that gives you a good overview of the course. It’s a good place to start. Please complete the High School Bound survey before you begin to work on your first level.

4.	<strong>How do I navigate through the levels and the quests?</strong> – When you click “The Course” on the top navigation bar, a submenu will open with each of the 4 levels. You can choose the level you are working on to go that level page. From the level page, you can click on any of the quests in that level. Please work in order.

5.	<strong>How do I track my progress through the course?</strong> – You earn quests and badges as you complete the activities and the levels. 

6.	<strong>How do I earn a badge?</strong> – You first need to finish the level associated with the badge.  You do that by completing the quests associated with that level and getting them approved by your teacher.  There are 4 levels.  Do them in order.  See the overview at http://hsc.nycdoelearns.org/big-picture/ 

7.	<strong>How do I earn a quest?</strong> – Click on the level and then on the name of a quest.  Follow the instructions and submit the quest for review. Your teacher will award you the quest if you’ve met all the requirements.

8.	<strong>What if a quest has a handout I’m supposed to work on? </strong>How do I do that? – If a handout is meant to be a resource for you to use during the quest, it will probably be a PDF document that you can download and save to your computer. Feel free to print it if you want. On the other hand, when there is a worksheet that you are supposed to complete and upload as part of your submission, it will probably be in a Microsoft Word document. In this case, download the document and save it on your computer. As you complete the worksheet, be sure to save your work. Upload your completed version to the submission area of the quest.

9.	<strong>How do I know what to submit?</strong> – Each quest includes instructions on how to complete the activity. The requested work may be simply typing up your results or your thinking in the box provided, or it might ask you to upload a document or worksheet.

10.	<strong>Where does my submission go?</strong> – After you submit your work in the provided submission box, it will be sent to a reviewer. The reviewer, who will most likely be your teacher, will go over your work and decide whether to approve it or ask you for more information. Once they have replied to your work, you will get a message under the “<strong>Progress</strong>” tab. This tab shows all of your work as either “pending”, “approved” “auto-approved” or “denied”.  If your work is “pending” see if there are comments telling you what needs to be improved.

11.	<strong>What if my teacher asks me to include more information?</strong>  Just answer their questions and put the information in the Comments area.  Then submit the comment.

12.	<strong>How will I know if I earned the quest?</strong> – All earned badges and quests will be displayed on the right side of the screen.

13.	<strong>Can I continue to work though the quests if I’m awaiting approval on the previous submissions?</strong> – Yes, you can continue to work on other quests while your work is under review.

14.	<strong>Do I need to earn quests in the order they are shown?</strong> – Yes, please work in order.  It will make more sense that way.
